Profit vs marginal cost

What this sweep is

  • Fix demand parameters (a, b) and evaluate a grid of marginal costs c (same cost for both firms).
  • For each cost, run many simulated episodes and plot the average per‑episode profit for each agent.
  • The dashed line is the Cournot‑Nash profit per firm, computed using the environment’s Nash equilibrium routine.
🧭
How to read: curves close to the dashed line indicate near‑Nash behavior under that information structure.
As c rises, equilibrium quantity and profits fall, so all curves slope downward.

Setup (from the notebook)

  • Demand is held fixed during the sweep (same (a, b) for all points).
  • Each point is averaged over many episodes (the notebook uses a large N to smooth the curves).
  • Matchups cover informed vs less‑informed play, plus self‑play for each agent type.

If you change the sweep grid or episode count and re‑run the notebook, regenerate the deck to refresh these plots.

Profit sweep

Perfect vs Partial (profits vs marginal cost)

Average profit as a function of marginal cost c, with Nash‑profit reference.

Interpretation

  • The Partial agent tracks the Nash reference closely across most of the grid.
  • The Perfect agent earns substantially less at low costs in this run, consistent with a more aggressive quantity choice that depresses price.
  • Around the mid‑range of c, the two curves converge and the relative advantage narrows.

These are empirical averages from the trained policies; small shifts can occur if you retrain or change evaluation settings.

Solid lines: RL agents. Dashed line: Nash profit per firm.Profit sweep

Partial vs No‑info (profits vs marginal cost)

Average profit as a function of marginal cost c, with Nash‑profit reference.

Interpretation

  • Both agents sit below the Nash line, with the gap largest when costs are low (where over‑production is most damaging).
  • In this run, the No‑info agent achieves higher profit than the Partial agent across the grid.
  • As c increases, profits compress and the two curves move closer together.

A useful follow‑up is to plot quantities vs c to see which agent is driving the price‑cutting via higher output.

Solid lines: RL agents. Dashed line: Nash profit per firm.Profit sweep

Self‑play: average profit vs marginal cost

Three self‑play curves on one plot (Perfect‑Perfect, Partial‑Partial, No‑info‑No‑info).

Interpretation

  • Perfect vs Perfect essentially overlaps the Nash reference, indicating near‑equilibrium play under full observability.
  • Partial vs Partial is below Nash, but approaches it more closely as marginal cost rises.
  • No‑info vs No‑info yields the lowest profits throughout, consistent with information constraints leading to less efficient strategic adjustment.
Solid lines: RL agents. Dashed line: Nash profit per firm.Profit sweep

Across tests (test environment)

Grouped bars show Agent 1 vs Agent 2 average profits per test.

Visual aid generated from the table values (not an additional notebook output).

Quick read

Summary

Takeaways

What the plots show

  • With full information, learned behavior tracks Nash more closely.
  • Reducing observability shifts quantities away from Nash, often toward overproduction at low costs.
  • When both players are under‑informed, profits can fall substantially in the evaluation scenario.
